gomodel:SYNGO_2794  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.3: \"Tetanus-induced nuclear accumulation of β-catenin\"\n- \"we tested the hypothesis that activity-induced Wnt release activates intracellular signaling pathways\"\n- \"Quantification of nuclear β-catenin signals of randomly selected DG granule cells showed that tetanus significantly increased β-catenin signals in the nuclei at 15 and 30 min after stimulations (Fig. 3, a-d).\"\n- \"We also found that APV completely abolished tetanus-induced nuclear accumulations of β-catenin (Fig. 3, e-h), indicating an essential role of NMDA receptors in tetanus-induced activation of the canonical Wnt/β-catenin pathway. In support of the activation of Wnt/β-catenin signaling after tetanic stimulations, we observed, based on a DNA microarray analysis,3 that tetanus up-regulated mRNAs of several Wnt target genes (Fig. 3m); these Wnt target genes included Dll1 (41, 42), Wisp-2 (43), Cldn1 (44), Fas (45), and CDD44 (46).\"\n- \"we investigated whether blockade of released Wnts can abolish tetanus-induced nuclear accumulation of β-catenin. To this end, we treated hippocampal slices with purified Frizzled-8-Fc (5 μg/ml), which is a Wnt scavenger (47). The results showed that Frizzled-8-Fc treatment abolished tetanus-induced nuclear accumulation of β-catenin (Fig. 3, i-l). \\\". Experimental description: - \"Hippocampal slices (400 μm) were prepared from 3-4-week mice...\"\n- Species of recombinant Wnt3a used in Fig.5 is not stated in the paper." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2018-06-01" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_2794" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

